Looking at this proof goal, I need to show that for any two pairs `(a₁, b₁)` and `(a₂, b₂)` in `α × β`, their probabilities are equal when sampling uniformly from the product type.

The key insight is that:
- `Pr[= (a₁, b₁) | ...] = Pr[= a₁ | $ᵗ α] * Pr[= b₁ | $ᵗ β]` (from the already simplified goal)
- `Pr[= (a₂, b₂) | ...] = Pr[= a₂ | $ᵗ α] * Pr[= b₂ | $ᵗ β]`
- By `SampleableType`, all elements in `α` have equal probability, and all elements in `β` have equal probability
- Therefore both products are equal

```lean
instance (α β : Type) [Fintype α] [Fintype β] [Inhabited α] [Inhabited β]
    [SampleableType α] [SampleableType β] : SampleableType (α × β) where
  selectElem := (·, ·) <$> ($ᵗ α) <*> ($ᵗ β)
  mem_support_selectElem x := by sorry
  probOutput_selectElem_eq := by
    simp only [Prod.forall, probOutput_seq_map_prod_mk_eq_mul,
      probOutput_uniformSample, forall_const, implies_true]
    intros a₁ b₁ a₂ b₂
    rw [SampleableType.probOutput_selectElem_eq a₁ a₂, 
        SampleableType.probOutput_selectElem_eq b₁ b₂]
```
